shire, England","Livesey, Lancashire, England":"Livesey, Lancashire, England","Withnall, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Kurt.","Swiss German and South German: from an Alemannic pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Buro  ."]},{"name":"Burgh","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":79,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictio